# THE config file for a docker deployment. Copy to `.env` (gitignored) and edit; compose reads it
# automatically from this directory, so nothing has to be exported or sourced:
#
#     cp .env.example .env && chmod 600 .env
#     docker compose -f docker-compose.vre.yml up -d --build     # whole VRE, one image
#     docker compose up -d --build                               # core only, one image per app
#
# For the VRE (demo) deployment this is the ONLY file outside the image -- the service roster is
# baked in. Values on the command line still work and take precedence over this file, but they land
# in your shell history and in `ps`, so prefer the file for the two secrets.

# ---- required ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# The FSDB on the host; mounted read-only at /mnt/data/fsdb. Start with a small slice: the
# services reduce the whole thing into RAM at load.
DDP_FSDB_ROOT=/mnt/data/full_fsdb/slices/mariapia/fsdb


# ---- identity / ports ----------------------------------------------------------------------
# Must be able to READ the FSDB bind-mount. `id -u`:`id -g`. Use 0:0 to run as root, which is what
# the in-container sshd needs in order to start.
DDP_USER=1000:1000
# Host port for the gateway (the only published HTTP port) -> http://localhost:7080/
DDP_PUBLISHED_PORT=7080
# Start the in-container debug sshd (1) or not (0). It only actually starts when the container runs
# as root, i.e. DDP_USER=0:0; otherwise the entrypoint logs why and carries on.
DDP_SSHD=1

# ---- which services start ------------------------------------------------------------------
# The tunnel services are behind compose PROFILES, so a plain `docker compose up` starts only
# gateway + st + sl. Setting COMPOSE_PROFILES here makes the tunnel part of the normal stack, so
# one `docker compose up` launches everything -- no --profile flag to remember.
#   tunnel        ephemeral trycloudflare.com URL, no account, no token
#   tunnel-token  your named tunnel (needs CLOUDFLARE_TUNNEL_TOKEN below)
# A profile ADDS to the default services, it does not replace them.
COMPOSE_PROFILES=

# ---- where the code comes from (VRE image only) ---------------------------------------------
# PINNED to the exact SHAs of the stable 2026-07-23 demo, so this rebuilds byte-for-byte instead of
# tracking moving branches. To follow the latest again, blank a REF (empty = that repo's default
# branch: ddpa_layout is on `master`, the others on `main`), or set a newer SHA/tag.
#
# didipcv itself is a PRIVATE repo, so it cannot be cloned anonymously as a build context -- build
# it from a local checkout with DIDIPCV_CONTEXT=. (the image was built this way for the demo). To
# build didipcv from GitHub instead, make the repo public (and push the didip-vre stage), then set
# DIDIPCV_CONTEXT to the git URL and DIDIPCV_REF to a SHA.
DIDIPCV_CONTEXT=.
DIDIPCV_REF=ec755627eb664d736b8b2af3b7dab38078a18e3b
# The three apps are public and pip-installed from GitHub at these exact commits:
LAYOUT_REF=1e846206b60ade58462fda281a43eae14a1fb292
CEI_REF=02446d3d7d223566c1ada02cc941724bdb3eaf35
TEXTURE_REF=d2da22f652bde48daa1d9c6c8cef3b29d8333269
# Install PyTorch (CPU) in the base image? Empty = no (smaller image). Set to 1 to enable.
# REQUIRED for cei2json: its dependency pylelemmatize imports torch unconditionally, so cei exits
# at startup without it. Leave empty if you are not running cei and want a lean image.
WITH_TORCH=1

# ---- secrets -------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Manual password gate on the gateway. Empty = no gate. The first correct answer whitelists that
# client IP until the gateway restarts.
DDP_GATEWAY_PASSWORD=

# Cloudflare named tunnel (compose profile `tunnel-token`). From the Zero Trust dashboard, where
# you also map the hostname to http://gateway:8080. The `tunnel` profile needs NO token -- it
# prints an ephemeral trycloudflare.com URL to its log instead.
CLOUDFLARE_TUNNEL_TOKEN=

# ---- tunnel / reverse-proxy correctness ----------------------------------------------------
# SET THIS WHENEVER A TUNNEL OR FRONT PROXY IS IN PLAY -- it is not optional hardening.
# The sidecar sits on the docker bridge, so without it every visitor arrives wearing the SAME
# address (one password admits everybody) AND that address is "local", which makes /health and
# /roster publicly readable -- /roster lists every backend's internal url.
# DDP_TRUSTED_PROXY_CIDR=172.16.0.0/12
DDP_TRUSTED_PROXY_CIDR=
